[1]
Date: Tue, 21 Oct 2003
From: Dr. Dale Carroll <DCARROLL@RHCC.com>

As Field Marshal Sir William Slim stated during WW II in
Burma..."Doctors don't prevent malaria...Commanders do!" He goes on
to say that once he sacked ("fired") a couple of his commanders with
high rates of malaria; the remaining commanders got the point and
instituted rigorous command-directed and -observed malaria
prophylaxis. The Post article does a disservice to the troops. The
health of the command is the commander's responsibility. "Sack" the
commander and the next time we deploy troops to endemic areas I
suspect the rates will be significantly lower!.
--
Dale A. Carroll, MD, MPH
Sr. VP - Medical Affairs and Performance Improvement
Rockingham Memorial Hospital
235 Cantrell Ave.
Harrisonburg, VA 22801
540.564.7060 - tel
540.433.4576 - fax
<dcarroll@rhcc.com>
