[2]
Date: Tue, 21 Oct 2003
From: Johannes Schaefer <schaefer-johannes@t-online.de>

I do not entirely agree with the moderator's comment that it is
comforting that non-compliance rather than direct failure of the drug
is responsible for the cases of malaria among US soldiers in Liberia.
No prophylactic regime can be effective without adherence. Adherence
is more than compliance -- it depends on education, motivation, and
active cooperation of the client. Non-adherence is a serious issue,
and probably reflects information and communication deficits that
need to be addressed.
Dr. med. J. Schaefer
Tropenklinik
Tuebingen, Germany
<schaefer-johannes@t-online.de>
[ProMED thank Dr Dale Carroll and Dr Johannes Schaeffer for sending
their comments. We certainly agree with Dr Schaeffer's comment that
communication deficits need to be addressed. This is more directly
expressed in Dr Carroll's comment, which places the responsibility
for non-compliance on the army. - Mod.EP]
